<item>
  <title>The Laundry Quarter Recurrence: A Birthday Problem Estimation</title>
  <dc:creator>Connor Lockhart</dc:creator>
  <link>https://conair94.github.io/Quarto/posts/laundry-quarter-estimation/</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 





<p>Have you ever wondered if the quarter you just dropped into the laundry machine is one you’ve held before? A friend recently asked me this very question. A solution can be derived from the same idea as the <strong>Generalized Birthday Problem</strong>, the odds might be higher than you’d expect.</p>
<section id="the-math" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-math">The Math</h2>
<p>To estimate this, we consider: - <strong><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n"></strong>: The total number of quarters you’ve handled over a period of time. - <strong><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N"></strong>: The total pool of quarters in circulation in your local area.</p>
<p>The true probability <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?P"> that at least two quarters in your sample of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n"> are the same is given by:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?P(n,%20N)%20=%201%20-%20%5Cprod_%7Bi=0%7D%5E%7Bn-1%7D%20%5Cleft(1%20-%20%5Cfrac%7Bi%7D%7BN%7D%5Cright)"></p>
<section id="deriving-the-true-probability" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="deriving-the-true-probability">Deriving the True Probability</h3>
<p>To find the probability of at least one collision, it is easier to calculate the probability of <strong>no</strong> collisions and subtract it from 1.</p>
<p>If we have a pool of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N"> quarters and we pick <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n"> of them: 1. The first quarter can be anything (<img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N/N"> chance of being “new”). 2. The second quarter must be different from the first (<img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(N-1)/N"> chance). 3. The <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?i">-th quarter must be different from all previous <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?i-1"> quarters (<img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(N-(i-1))/N"> chance).</p>
<p>The probability that all <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n"> quarters are unique is the product of these individual probabilities: <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?P(%5Ctext%7Bunique%7D)%20=%20%5Cfrac%7BN%7D%7BN%7D%20%5Ctimes%20%5Cfrac%7BN-1%7D%7BN%7D%20%5Ctimes%20%5Cfrac%7BN-2%7D%7BN%7D%20%5Ctimes%20%5Cdots%20%5Ctimes%20%5Cfrac%7BN-(n-1)%7D%7BN%7D"> <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?P(%5Ctext%7Bunique%7D)%20=%20%5Cprod_%7Bi=0%7D%5E%7Bn-1%7D%20%5Cleft(%5Cfrac%7BN-i%7D%7BN%7D%5Cright)%20=%20%5Cprod_%7Bi=0%7D%5E%7Bn-1%7D%20%5Cleft(1%20-%20%5Cfrac%7Bi%7D%7BN%7D%5Cright)"></p>
<p>Thus, the probability of at least one duplicate is <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?1%20-%20P(%5Ctext%7Bunique%7D)">.</p>
</section>
<section id="deriving-the-approximation" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="deriving-the-approximation">Deriving the Approximation</h3>
<p>For large <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N"> and relatively small <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n">, we can use the Taylor series expansion for the exponential function, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?e%5E%7B-x%7D%20%5Capprox%201%20-%20x"> for small <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?x">. Conversely, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?1%20-%20%5Cfrac%7Bi%7D%7BN%7D%20%5Capprox%20e%5E%7B-i/N%7D">.</p>
<p>Substituting this into our product: <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?P(%5Ctext%7Bunique%7D)%20%5Capprox%20%5Cprod_%7Bi=0%7D%5E%7Bn-1%7D%20e%5E%7B-i/N%7D%20=%20e%5E%7B-%5Csum_%7Bi=0%7D%5E%7Bn-1%7D%20%5Cfrac%7Bi%7D%7BN%7D%7D"></p>
<p>The sum of the first <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n-1"> integers is <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cfrac%7Bn(n-1)%7D%7B2%7D">, so: <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?P(%5Ctext%7Bunique%7D)%20%5Capprox%20e%5E%7B-%5Cfrac%7Bn(n-1)%7D%7B2N%7D%7D"></p>
<p>This gives us the familiar approximation for the birthday problem: <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?P(n,%20N)%20%5Capprox%201%20-%20e%5E%7B-%5Cfrac%7Bn(n-1)%7D%7B2N%7D%7D"></p>
</section>
<section id="estimating-the-local-pool-n" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="estimating-the-local-pool-n">Estimating the Local Pool (<img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N">)</h3>
<p>Rather than guessing <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N">, we can estimate it based on the population. If we know the total number of quarters in the US (<img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Q_%7Btotal%7D">) and the US population (<img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Pop_%7Btotal%7D">), we can estimate the local pool for a metro area with population <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?Pop_%7Bmetro%7D">:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?N%20=%20Q_%7Btotal%7D%20%5Ctimes%20%5Cfrac%7BPop_%7Bmetro%7D%7D%7BPop_%7Btotal%7D%7D%20%5Ctimes%20(1%20-%20%5Ctext%7BLoss%20Rate%7D)"></p>
<p>The “Loss Rate” accounts for quarters that are “dormant” (in jars or couch cushions) or have been lost to the general economy.</p>
</section>
</section>
